[src:shadow-dom-deep/css-part] It’s been available across browsers since July 2020.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/css-part] The **`::part`** CSS pseudo-element represents any element within a shadow tree that has a matching `part` attribute.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/css-part] The global `part` attribute makes a shadow tree element visible to its parent DOM.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/css-part] The part names declared using the `part` attribute are used as the parameter of the `::part()` pseudo-element.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/css-part] In this way, you can apply CSS styles to elements in the shadow tree from outside of it.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/css-part] Part names are similar to CSS classes: multiple elements can have the same part name, and a single element can have multiple part names.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/css-part] All part names used in `::part()` pseudo-element must be present in the `part` value declared on the shadow tree element but the order of the part names doesn't matter, i.e., the selectors `::part(tab active)` and `::part(active tab)` are the same.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/css-part] The `::part()` pseudo-element is only visible to the parent DOM.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/css-part] This means that when a shadow tree is nested, the parts are not visible to any ancestors other than the direct parent.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/css-part] The `exportparts` attribute solves this limitation by explicitly exporting already defined `part` names, making them globally stylable.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/css-part] Pseudo-classes (such as `::part(label):hover`) can be appended to the `::part()` selector, but structural pseudo-classes that match based on tree information, such as `:empty` and `:last-child`, cannot be appended.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/css-part] Additional pseudo-elements, such as `::before`, can be appended to the `::part()` selector, but additional `::part()` element can't be appended.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/css-part] For example, `::part(confirm-button)::part(active)` never matches anything, i.e, it is not the same as `::part(confirm-button active)`.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/css-part] This is because doing so would expose more structural information than is intended.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] In software systems, **encapsulation** refers to the bundling of data with the mechanisms or methods that operate on the data.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] It may also refer to the limiting of direct access to some of that data, such as an object's components.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] Essentially, encapsulation prevents external code from being concerned with the internal workings of an object.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] Encapsulation allows developers to present a consistent interface that is independent of its internal implementation.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] As one example, encapsulation can be used to hide the values or state of a structured data object inside a class.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] This prevents clients from directly accessing this information in a way that could expose hidden implementation details or violate state invariance maintained by the methods.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] Encapsulation also encourages programmers to put all the code that is concerned with a certain set of data in the same class, which organizes it for easy comprehension by other programmers.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] Encapsulation is a technique that encourages decoupling.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] All object-oriented programming (OOP) systems support encapsulation, but encapsulation is not unique to OOP.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] Implementations of abstract data types, modules, and libraries also offer encapsulation.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] The similarity has been explained by programming language theorists in terms of existential types.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] The second definition reflects that in many object-oriented languages, and other related fields, the components are not hidden automatically and this can be overridden.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] Thus, information hiding is defined as a separate notion by those who prefer the second definition.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] The features of encapsulation are supported using classes in most object-oriented languages, although other alternatives also exist.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] Encapsulation may also refer to containing a repetitive or complex process in a single unit to be invoked.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] Object-oriented programming facilitates this at both the method and class levels.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] This definition is also applicable to procedural programming.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] The authors of *Design Patterns* discuss the tension between inheritance and encapsulation at length and state that in their experience, designers overuse inheritance.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] They claim that inheritance often breaks encapsulation, given that inheritance exposes a subclass to the details of its parent's implementation.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] As described by the yo-yo problem, overuse of inheritance and therefore encapsulation, can become too complicated and hard to debug.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] Under the definition that encapsulation "can be used to hide data members and member functions", the internal representation of an object is generally hidden outside of the object's definition.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] Typically, only the object's own methods can directly inspect or manipulate its fields.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] Hiding the internals of the object protects its integrity by preventing users from setting the internal data of the component into an invalid or inconsistent state.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] A supposed benefit of encapsulation is that it can reduce system complexity, and thus increase robustness, by allowing the developer to limit the interdependencies between software components.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] Some languages like Smalltalk and Ruby only allow access via object methods, but most others (e.g., C++, C#, Delphi or Java) offer the programmer some control over what is hidden, typically via keywords like `public` and `private`.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] ISO C++ standard refers to `protected`, `private` and `public` as "access specifiers" and that they do not "hide any information".
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] Information hiding is accomplished by furnishing a compiled version of the source code that is interfaced via a header file.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] Almost always, there is a way to override such protection – usually via reflection API (Ruby, Java, C#, etc.), sometimes by mechanism like name mangling (Python), or special keyword usage like `friend` in C++.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] Systems that provide object-level capability-based security (adhering to the object-capability model) are an exception, and guarantee strong encapsulation.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] Languages like C++, C#, Java, PHP, Swift, and Delphi offer ways to restrict access to data fields.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] Encapsulation is also possible in non-object-oriented languages.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] In C, for example, a structure can be declared in the public API via the header file for a set of functions that operate on an item of data containing data members that are not accessible to clients of the API with the `extern` keyword.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] Clients call the API functions to allocate, operate on, and deallocate objects of an opaque data type.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] The contents of this type are known and accessible only to the implementation of the API functions; clients cannot directly access its contents.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] Below is an example of Python, which does not support variable access restrictions.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/encapsulation-computer-programming] However, the convention is that a variable whose name is prefixed by an underscore should be considered private.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/htmlslotelement] The **`HTMLSlotElement`** interface of the Shadow DOM API enables access to the name and assigned nodes of an HTML `<slot>` element.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/htmlslotelement] A string used to get and set the slot's name.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/htmlslotelement] Sets the manually assigned nodes for this slot to the given nodes.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/htmlslotelement] Returns a sequence of the nodes assigned to this slot.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/htmlslotelement] If the `flatten` option is set to `true`, it returns a sequence of both the nodes assigned to this slot, and the nodes assigned to any other slots that are descendants of this slot.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/htmlslotelement] If no assigned nodes are found, it returns the slot's fallback content.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/htmlslotelement] Returns a sequence of the elements assigned to this slot (and no other nodes).
[src:shadow-dom-deep/htmlslotelement] If the `flatten` option is set to `true`, it returns a sequence of both the elements assigned to this slot, and the elements assigned to any other slots that are descendants of this slot.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/htmlslotelement] If no assigned elements are found, it returns the slot's fallback content.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/htmlslotelement] Listen to these events using `addEventListener()` or by assigning an event listener to the `oneventname` property of this interface.
[src:shadow-dom-deep/htmlslotelement] Fired on an `HTMLSlotElement` instance (`<slot>` element) when the node(s) contained in that slot change.
